<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-906-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 906 808  OV: 07 906 766.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 20 1989 v6 n46 p105(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AC-powered workhorse. (Microelectronic Technologies Inc. 2400Xmodem) (Hardware Review) (one of five evaluations in 'Pocketmodems let users travel with power, flexibility') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kramer, Matt.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microelectronic Technologies Inc's 2400X is a feature-laden,reliable modem that runs on AC only.andP;  The modem is built to beused with desktop equipment, and includes 9-pin serial port,conventional 25-pin RS-232C connections and two telephone jacks.andO;The 2400X, $299, also includes Smith Microsoftware Inc's QuicklinkII communications software.andP;  Users who want the modem-serial portcombination will do well with the 2400X.andP;  Buyers who wereattracted to the 2400X because of its impressive fax capabilitiesare similarly impressed with the 2400X's other qualities includingease of use, plethora of indicator lights and reliability.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microelectronic Technologies Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Microelectronic Technologies 2400X (Modem).andO;Topic:     ModemsEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AC-Powered WorkhorseandM;MICROELECTRONIC TECHNOLOGIES INC.,andM;2400X, $299 (INCLUDES SMITHandM;MICROSOFTWARE INC.'S QUICKLINK IIandM;COMMUNICATIONS SOFTWARE)andM;Microelectronic Technologies' 2400X offers a bulkier (5-1/2 inches by 4-1/2inches) but more feature-rich version of the serial-port/modem combinationthat Xecom offers with its FeedThru Modem 2400.andM;Using a form factor close to that of a conventional desktop modem, the 2400Xincludes a 9-pin serial port and conventional 25-pin RS-232C connection inthe back, along with dual telephone jacks for connections to the wall jackand a telephone.andM;Along with a speaker, the front panel offers a full set of status indicatorlights, including high-speed communications, auto answer, carrier detect,on-hook, receive/send data, terminal ready and modem ready.andP;  A simple switchtoggles between the modem function and the serial port.andM;The modem is also notable for not using internal switches (configuration issoftware-loadable).andP;  Unlike the Xecom unit, which can be converted into aportable by adding a battery, this unit is built for workhorse desktopoperation.andM;If a buyer needs a 2,400-bps modem and wants to share a serial port, thisunit will perform just fine.andM;Microelectronic Technologies Inc. can be contacted in Hopkinton, Mass., at(508) 435-9057.andM;----------Buyers say: Reliable modemandM;Denis Rubinstein, vice president of Expansion Strategies Inc., a marketingand consulting company in Hartford, N.Y., uses Microelectronic Technologies'2400XS modem, which has the same size and features as the 2400X, with addedfax capabilities.andM;Although the fax capabilities are what attracted Rubinstein to the 2400XS, hehas been pleased with its other features.andP;  &quot;What helps many of my PC users isthe pass-through serial port,&quot; he said.andM;Connie Mather, an assistant professor at the University of Connecticut, inStorrs, said she liked the 2400X's small size and its reliability.andP;  Otherfeatures that stood out were the modem's ease of use and its full set ofindicator lights, she said.andM;</TEXT></DOC>